,"nl":{"–":"Overleden","–1616":"–1616","1605–Male":"1605–Overleden","–Female":"Overleden","1689":"1689","1688":"1688","1642":"1642","1620":"1620","1587":"1587","about 1603":"circa 1603","1651":"1651","1585":"1585","1605":"1605","1616":"1616","ABT 1605":"circa 1605","england":"England","of Frolesworth, Leicester, England":"Frolesworth, Leicestershire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","England, United Kingdom":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"–":"Deceased","–1616":"–1616","1605–Male":"1605–Deceased","–Female":"Deceased","1689":"1689","1688":"1688","1642":"1642","1620":"1620","1587":"1587","about 1603":"about 1603","1651":"1651","1585":"1585","1605":"1605","1616":"1616","ABT 1605":"about 1605","england":"England","of Frolesworth, Leicester, England":"Frolesworth, Leicestershire, England, United Kingdom","England, United Kingdom":"England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Emmett","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English:","from the Middle English female personal name <i>Emmot</i>, an interchangeable pet form of <i>Emma</i>, first introduced into England from France by the Normans, among whom it was extremely popular. Compare   Emm  .","habitational name from either Emmot near Colne (Lancashire) or Emmett in Bishop's Tawton (Devon). The former is from Old English <i>ēa-gemōt</i> ‘junction of the streams’. The latter is from Old English <i>emnet</i> ‘plain, level ground’, referring to the flat land here."],"variants":[{"name":"Emm","meanings":["English (Wiltshire): variant of   Imm  ."]},{"name":"Emmitt","meanings":["English (Lincolnshire): variant of   Emmett  ."]},{"name":"Emmet","meanings":["English (Yorkshire and Lancashire): variant of   Emmett  ."]},{"name":"Emmott","meanings":["English (Yorkshire and Lancashire): variant of   Emmett  ."]},{"name":"Emerson","meanings":["English: patronymic meaning ‘son of <i>Emery</i>’, or possibly a variant of <i>Emmeson</i>, from the Middle English personal name <i>Emmott</i> + <i>-son</i>, with later shortening of the first element (see   Emmett  ). See   Emery   and compare   Empson  .","History: The poet and essayist Ralph Waldo Emerson (1803–82) was born in Boston of a line on his father's side that can be traced back through preachers to the first colonial generation. The name Emerson was brought over from England independently by various other people, including a Thomas Emerson who settled at Ipswich, MA, <i>c.</i> 1636."]},{"name":"Emison","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Herschell, Hershel.","English: variant of <b>Emmison</b>, a metronymic from   Emmett  . This surname is found mainly in TN.","Americanized form of some similar (like-sounding) Jewish (Ashkenazic) surname."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705207,"age":1,"year":"1585","julianDay":2299970,"title":"The First English Colony is Established in America","description":"England established its first colony in North America in 1585 as a way to generate additional wealth. The colony was named Virginia, after the virgin Queen Elizabeth I.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705208,"age":3,"year":"1587","julianDay":2300700,"title":"Elizabeth I Signs Death Warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots","description":"Elizabeth I signed the death warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots, on February 1, 1587, as she was found guilty of plotting to assasinate Elizabeth. Mary, Queen of Scots, was beheaded at Fotheringhay Castle in England on February 8, 1587.","url":"https://www.elizabethi.org/mary_queen_of_scots/","urlTitle":"Elizabeth I.org - Mary Queen of Scots","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705212,"age":36,"year":"1620","julianDay":2312753,"title":"The Pilgrims Board the Mayflower","description":"\"The Pilgrims boarded the Mayflower in search of religious freedom in the New World in September 1620. The Mayflower set sail from Plymouth, England, with 102 passengers, 40 of whom called themselves \"\"Saints.\"\" After two stormy months at sea, the ship reached the New World. Nearly half of the group died during their first winter due to malnutrition and the harsh New England winter.\"","url":"https://www.themayflowersociety.org/the-pilgrims/pilgrim-history","urlTitle":"The Mayflower Society - Pilgrim History","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705213,"age":58,"year":"1642","toYear":"1651","julianDay":2320789,"title":"The English Civil War","description":"A series of conflicts regarding England's governance during the years 1642 to 1651 is now known as The English Civil War. Charles I summoned supporters to join him against his enemies in Parliament. In October 1642, nearly 10,000 men fought for Charles I and chased Parliament across the River Tamar. Fighting continued for years and was finally ended at the Battle of Worcester on September 3, 1651, with a Parliamentarian victory.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705216,"age":104,"year":"1688","toYear":"1689","julianDay":2337590,"title":"Glorious Revolution","description":"The Glorious Revolution brought the downfall of Catholic King James II and the reign of his Protestant daughter Mary and her Dutch husband, William III of Orange.","url":"http://www.bbc.co.uk/history/british/civil_war_revolution/glorious_revolution_01.shtml","urlTitle":"BBC - Glorious Revolution","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"Emmett was born in England. She married John Hall about 1603, in England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son."},"et":{"–":"Surnud","–1616":"–1616","1605–Male":"1605–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1689":"1689","1688":"1688","1642":"1642","1620":"1620","1587":"1587","about 1603":"umbes 1603","1651":"1651","1585":"1585","1605":"1605","1616":"1616","ABT 1605":"umbes 1605","england":"England","of Frolesworth, Leicester, England":"Frolesworth, Leicestershire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England, United Kingdom":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"–":"Kuollut","–1616":"–1616","1605–Male":"1605–Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","1689":"1689","1688":"1688","1642":"1642","162